{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","data":{"fields":{"description":"# S7 — Documentation, ADR, and regenerated references for MCP auth\n\n## Why\nThe capability must be usable and auditable by a third-party operator, and the design decisions +\nresidual risks must be recorded for maintainers and the rigorous security review. This story writes\nthe operator guide and the ADR, and does the FINAL consistency check of the derived reference\nartifacts (each key-adding story S1–S6 already registers ITS keys and regenerates its slice; S7\nconfirms the integrated whole is consistent).\n\n## What\n- New `docs/mcp-auth.md` — the operator guide:\n  - How to enable the HTTP transport + auth; each of the five verifier modes (`static`, `jwt`,\n    `introspection`, `proxy`, `custom`) with a flat-config example each, and the closed\n    `auth_strategies` vocabulary. State the flat-schema limitation: **one instance per strategy type**\n    (for multiple issuers, use the `custom` verifier).\n  - The **security model:** resource-server-only (no AS/DCR); the composite as the single audience/\n    fail-closed choke point (every token's `resource` == `auth_resource_server_url`, RFC 8707); no\n    token passthrough; DNS-rebinding/Origin defaults; the non-loopback bind requirements (allowlists\n    + TLS-at-edge ack); tokens/secrets never logged.\n  - **Behind-a-proxy deployment:** TLS terminates at the edge (nginx/ALB) and rebar binds loopback;\n    the external host must be in `http_allowed_hosts` and the external origin in `http_allowed_origins`;\n    `auth_resource_server_url` MUST be the external https URL (it drives the served PRM `resource` and\n    the `WWW-Authenticate: resource_metadata` URL — NOT the request scheme), and is validated https\n    for non-loopback. Include a concrete nginx/ALB header + allowlist example.\n  - **The three interactive-client connection paths** (so RS-only isn't experienced as \"can't\n    connect\"): (1) static bearer via Claude Code `--header \"Authorization: Bearer …\"` / Claude.ai\n    `static_headers` — pairs with the static verifier; (2) automatic OAuth when the org IdP supports\n    DCR or CIMD (Keycloak/Auth0/Okta can); (3) pre-registered `--client-id`/`--client-secret` for\n    IdPs without anonymous DCR (Entra, Cognito). Note rebar serves the PRM that drives discovery.\n  - **Residual risks (documented, not fixed here):** authenticated ≠ authorized — any authenticated\n    principal wields rebar's full ambient authority (writes auto-push; `reconcile live` uses rebar's\n    own creds) gated only by server-level `required_scopes` and the existing `REBAR_MCP_READONLY`/\n    `ALLOW_JIRA_SYNC`/`ALLOW_LLM` env gates, which now also gate remote actors; per-tool\n    scope→capability authorization is deferred; rate-limiting/brute-force is delegated to the edge\n    proxy in v1, with mandated ≥128-bit static tokens (document the generator one-liner).\n- A new ADR under `docs/adr/` recording: the resource-server-only decision (no AS / no DCR); building\n  our own verifiers on the official SDK seam vs adopting standalone `fastmcp` (semver-exempt auth,\n  CVE history); the composite audience choke point (motivated by the SDK having no `.resource`\n  backstop + the audience-confusion precedent PVE-2026-93393); the five verifier modes; the transport\n  hardening (citing GHSA-9h52-p55h-vw2f DNS-rebinding, oauth2-proxy CVE-2026-40575 forwarded-header,\n  CVE-2026-27124 confused-deputy); and the explicitly deferred items (AS/DCR, per-tool authz,\n  in-process rate-limiting, AWS deployment).\n- **Final reference/manifest consistency check:** confirm `docs/mcp-reference.md`/`docs/env-vars.md`\n  are fully regenerated for the integrated set of new keys and `scripts/check_server_manifest.py` +\n  the reference drift gates pass on the combined branch (S1–S6 each regenerated their slice; S7\n  verifies the union).\n\n## Approach & rationale\nDocumentation-and-ADR story sequenced last so it documents the *actually shipped* surface (S1–S6);\nregeneration (not hand-editing) keeps the derived docs authoritative and drift-gated. A docs/mechanical\nleaf — no runtime behavior.\n\n## Scope\n`docs/mcp-auth.md`, the ADR, and the final reference/manifest consistency verification only. No code\nbehavior. Subset of the epic. Depends on S1–S6 (documents them).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] `docs/mcp-auth.md` exists and covers: enabling HTTP+auth; all five verifier modes with a\n      flat-config example each + the `auth_strategies` vocabulary + the one-instance-per-type\n      limitation; the security model (composite audience choke point, fail-closed, no passthrough);\n      behind-a-proxy deployment (TLS + allowlists + `auth_resource_server_url` drives discovery URLs)\n      with an nginx/ALB example; the three interactive-client connection paths; and the residual risks\n      (authenticated≠authorized + gate interaction, per-tool authz deferral, rate-limiting delegation,\n      static-token entropy) — observable oracle: the file exists and a docs link/section check passes.\n- [ ] An ADR file exists under `docs/adr/` recording the resource-server-only + build-own decision,\n      the composite audience choke point, the five modes, the transport-hardening CVE citations, and\n      the deferred items.\n- [ ] `docs/mcp-reference.md` and `docs/env-vars.md` are fully regenerated for the integrated new-key\n      set and the CI drift gates for them and for `server.json` pass on the combined branch\n      (observable oracle: `make test` / the manifest-check job is green with all new keys present).\n- [ ] `make lint && make test` pass (docs/mechanical leaf; no typecheck-relevant code added here).\n\n## Compatibility\nDocs only; no runtime or dependency change beyond what S1–S6 introduced."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784068932638770001,"uuid":"7e4f05a8-f599-4ec5-a8e3-91b74ca9949b"}